06/21/2022

Descriptive Statistics

  • Type of data:

    • Quantitative variables: Whole or real numbered data
      • e.g. Age, BMI
    • Categorical variables: Falls into mutually exclusive categories
      • May or may not have a natural ordering (nominal vs. ordinal)
      • e.g. Biological sex, Race/ethnicity, Education level

  • Typical goal in data analysis is understanding the relationship (associations) between pairs of variables.

  • Today we’ll focus on bivariate descriptive statistics

  • Bivariate descriptive statistics can provide initial clues about associations

Univariate data: Quantitative

Graphical summary: Histogram / Box Plot

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
hist(chs$weight)
boxplot(chs$weight, main = "Boxplot of chs$weight")

Univariate data: Quantitative

Numerical summary: Mean (sd) / Median (IQR)

mean(chs$weight); sd(chs$weight)
## [1] 64.6804
## [1] 15.99024
median(chs$weight); IQR(chs$weight)
## [1] 61.05
## [1] 17.925

Univariate data: Categorical

Graphical summary: Bar chart (or pie chart)

slices <- table(chs$race) # Get counts per race/ethnicity
lbls   <- names(slices) # Get labels
par(mfrow = c(1,2))

barplot(slices)
pie(slices, labels = lbls)

Quantitative vs. quantitative variables

Graphical summary: scatter plots

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(chs$height, chs$weight)
plot(chs$sulfate, chs$nitrate)

Many R packages for generating plots. ggplot2 is among the most popular.

Quantitative vs. quantitative

Numerical summary: Pearson correlation coefficient

\(r = corr(x,y) = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n (x_i - \bar{x}) (y_i - \bar{y})}{sd(x)sd(y)}\)

\(-1 \le r \le 1\)

Captures strength of linear relationship between \(x\) and \(y\)

cor(chs$height, chs$weight)
## [1] 0.450752
cor(chs$sulfate, chs$nitrate)
## [1] 0.8643069

Quantitative vs. quantitative 

x <- seq(-1, 1, by = 0.1)
y <- x^2
cor(y, x) # Close to 0 even if there is a relationship
## [1] 1.216307e-16

Quantitative vs. quantitative

Correlation examples

Source: Wikipedia

Quantitative vs. quantitative

Other measures of correlation exist:

  • Spearman’s \(\rho\)

  • Kendall’s \(\tau\)

These measures do not require an assumption on linearity but oftentimes have their own assumptions. For example, Spearman’s \(\rho\) captures monotonicity.

Correlation vs. Causation

Correlation does not imply causation!!!

http://www.tylervigen.com/spurious-correlations

Graphical summary: Box Plots

chs$sex = factor(chs$male, levels = 0:1, labels = c('F', 'M'))
boxplot(chs$height ~ chs$sex, main = 'Height by sex', 
        xlab = 'Sex', ylab='Height', col = 'steelblue')

Numerical summary: mean/sd or median/IQR by levels of the categorical variable

## 2       M 171.4741
aggregate(chs$height, by = list(chs$sex), FUN=sd)

Parting Comments

  • Assessing bivariate associations is a good preliminary step towards a thoughtful analysis.

  • These associations can be both quantified and tested for statistical significance (hypothesis testing)

  • More sophisticated methods (regression modeling) can be used to assess associations adjusting for other variables.

    • e.g. How does gender affect height after adjusting for age and race/ethnicity?

Parting Comments

  • Data can be presented in various formats
  • Clarity is important when communicating and summarizing data through graphs and tables.
    • Less is more
    • Niemi J. and Gelman A. (2011) Statistical Graphics – Making Information Clear and Beautiful. Significance. DOI:10.1111/j.1740-9713.2011.00512.x

Parting Comments

Several R packages have been developed recently that have improved data wrangling/cleaning and visualization.

  • See e.g. tidyverse which include both dplyr and ggplot2.
# ggplot2 package
ggplot(aes(x = sex, y = height), data = chs) +
  geom_boxplot()
